T1  - Rollover Risk and Credit Risk
AU  - HE, ZHIGUO
AU  - XIONG, WEI
Y1  - 2012/04/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01721.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 391
EP  - 430
VL  - 67
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01721.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Our model shows that deterioration in debt market liquidity leads to an increase in not only the liquidity premium of corporate bonds but also credit risk. The latter effect originates from firms' debt rollover. When liquidity deterioration causes a firm to suffer losses in rolling over its maturing debt, equity holders bear the losses while maturing debt holders are paid in full. This conflict leads the firm to default at a higher fundamental threshold. Our model demonstrates an intricate interaction between the liquidity premium and default premium and highlights the role of short-term debt in exacerbating rollover risk.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Are Stocks Really Less Volatile in the Long Run?
AU  - PÁSTOR, ĽUBOŠ
AU  - STAMBAUGH, ROBERT F.
Y1  - 2012/04/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01722.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 431
EP  - 478
VL  - 67
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01722.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT According to conventional wisdom, annualized volatility of stock returns is lower over long horizons than over short horizons, due to mean reversion induced by return predictability. In contrast, we find that stocks are substantially more volatile over long horizons from an investor's perspective. This perspective recognizes that parameters are uncertain, even with two centuries of data, and that observable predictors imperfectly deliver the conditional expected return. Mean reversion contributes strongly to reducing long-horizon variance but is more than offset by various uncertainties faced by the investor. The same uncertainties reduce desired stock allocations of long-horizon investors contemplating target-date funds.
ER  - 

